Hey everyone,

This year our team has decided to switch to WPILib Java in place of FRC LabVIEW. I have a couple questions.

Is there an option to auto run code when the robot turns on? With LabVIEW, it was a build specification named “FRC Robot Boot-Up Deployment”. If there is, could I get any pointers on how to use that?

This might be a ridiculous question, but how do you abort the code after it is deployed to the robot? You could press a red button in Robot Main.vi in LabVIEW to abort the code.

Thanks in advance, and good luck to all teams!

Ian Fettes
Lead Programmer, Team 5503

Ian_Fettes_5503:

Is there an option to auto run code when the robot turns on? With LabVIEW, it was a build specification named “FRC Robot Boot-Up Deployment”. If there is, could I get any pointers on how to use that?

https://docs.wpilib.org/en/latest/docs/zero-to-robot/step-4/creating-benchtop-test-program-cpp-java.html?highlight=robotinit#robot-initialization

Look at the “robotInit” method found here. All code in that method will be running on the initialization of your robot.

Ian_Fettes_5503:

This might be a ridiculous question, but how do you abort the code after it is deployed to the robot? You could press a red button in Robot Main.vi in LabVIEW to abort the code.

I’m not sure if I understand if I understand this correctly. Could you explain? Why would you need to abort? Is it an alternative to disabling the robot? I’m sure there is an equivalent in Java somewhere.

In Java, the code you send to the robot runs on start by default. This is unlike Labview where you have a softboot test where it runs on the robot but is not stored automatically.

In Java, there is no way that I am aware to run the softboot. This actually leads into your second question.

Because the code is actually running on the robot and is stored on the robot, the only cancel is the estop (or disable).

However, breaking changes do not normally brick the Rio even if you cannot get it to run (perhaps with a runtine error in robotInit() or robot periodic), you can still push new code to override it.

There are a few rare cases in which corrupted data can softbrick a Rio, but it is very rare. It happened to us twice, both times were because of mismatches between Java and Python. It is recoverable.

I feel that the Java (and other text-based language) error reporting is a lot easier to understand and troubleshoot than Labview was (at least for us) which also helps relieve the need for the above.

Ian_Fettes_5503:

This might be a ridiculous question, but how do you abort the code after it is deployed to the robot? You could press a red button in Robot Main.vi in LabVIEW to abort the code.

Not a bad question at all! The sticky point is that the existing mechanisms I’m aware of don’t map 1:1 with the thing you already know about. We’d need more details on what you’re looking to accomplish to recommend.

Two analogs I can think up quickly: The Driver Station has a “restart robot code” button that we’ll use frequently. The RIO has a button in it to reset as well. We do this pretty frequently while testing.

If you’re truly looking to stop the code from ever starting again without powering off the RIO, you can SSH into it and run a systemctl (I think) command to stop the process which runs (and relaunches) the code. But, it’s not very common, I can count on two fingers the number of times I’ve had to fiddle with it.

Welcome to the wonderful world of text-based programming!

Also worthwhile to note: Depending on what features you’re used to using in labview… there’s two tools you might find useful:

Single-Step Debugger
Glass Dashboard

Thanks for the warm welcome into text-based programming!

To clarify, when I deploy robot code to the robot, and I need to make changes and redeploy, is it at all possible to stop the previous version of robot code and deploy the new version without having to reboot the RIO?
